definition.value: Salts formally resulting from the reaction of hydrobromic acid with an organic base.
The substituent group formed by loss of a proton from azanide.

Compounds derived from oxoacids RkE(=O)l(OH)m (l =/= 0) by replacing =O by =NR; thus tautomers of amides. In organic chemistry an unspecified imidic acid is generally a carboximidic acid, RC(=NR)(OH).
A carboximidic acid that is the imidic acid tautomer of urea, H2NC(=NH)OH, and its hydrocarbyl derivatives.
A C-nitro compound that is entacapone in which the phenolic hydroxy group that is meta to the nitro group has been converted into the corresponding ethyl ether.
A C-nitro compound that is entacapone in which the phenolic hydroxy group that is meta to the nitro group has been converted into the corresponding methyl ether.
An organic heterobicyclic compound that consists of an imidazole ring ortho-fused to a pyridazine ring.
Any organonitrogen heterocyclic compound whose skeleton consists of a pyrazole ring that is ortho-fused to a pyridazine ring.
A member of the class of benzaldehydes that is vanillin in which the hydrogen ortho- to the hydroxy group is substituted by a nitro group.
A secondary amino compound that is (1R)-1-(naphthalen-1-yl)ethanamine in which one of the hydrogens attached to the nitrogen is substituted by a 3-[3-(trifluoromethyl)phenyl]propyl group.
A hydrochloride derived from equimolar amounts of cinacalcet and hydrogen chloride.
The simplest member of the class of methanediols that is methane in which two of the hydrogens have been substituted by hydroxy groups.

A monocarboxylic acid that is 3-phenylpropionic acid substituted by hydroxy groups at positions 3 and 4. Also known as dihydrocaffeic acid, it is a metabolite of caffeic acid and exhibits antioxidant activity.
A UDP-sugar having alpha-D-mannuronic acid as the sugar component.
An EC 2.1.1.* (methyltransferase) inhibitor that interferes with the action of catechol O-methyltransferase (EC 2.1.1.6).
A drug used in the treatment of Parkinson's disease.
A member of the class of benzaldehydes that is vanillin in which the methoxy group is replaced by an ethoxy group.
An alicyclic ketone that is cyclohexanone in which the pro-S hydrogens at positions 2, 3, and 4 are substituted by methoxy, (2E)-6-methylhept-2-en-2-yl, and trifluoroacetyl groups, respectively.
An alicyclic ketone that is cyclohexanone in which the pro-S hydrogens at positions 2, 3, and 4 are substituted by methoxy, (2E)-6-methylhept-2-en-2-yl, and acetyl groups, respectively.

An enoate ester obtained by formal condensation of the hydroxy function of (1R,2S,3S,4S)-4-formyl-2-methoxy-3-[(2E)-6-methylhept-2-en-2-yl]cyclohexanol with the carboxy group of 4-methoxycinnamic acid.

An alicyclic ketone that is cyclohexanone in which the pro-S hydrogens at positions 2, 3, and 4 are substituted by methoxy, (2E)-6-methylhept-2-en-2-yl, and perfluoro-2-hydroxypropan-2-yl groups, respectively.
